Jurisdiction decision rules:
- National: federal agencies (DCCEEW, MDBA, BoM, ACCC, Productivity
  Commission), inter-state bodies, cross-jurisdictional instruments.
- State / territory: pick the state whose agency or law is the
  primary actor. Look at: (a) named agency (e.g. Melbourne Water → Vic),
  (b) named Act (e.g. Water Management Act 2000 (NSW) → NSW),
  (c) URL domain (e.g. `.vic.gov.au`, `.nsw.gov.au`).
- If the article involves TWO states (e.g. a shared river basin not
  covered by MDBA), pick the state where the lead agency operates.

===========================================================================
VALID CONTENT TYPES (choose EXACTLY ONE — use the lowercase enum key)
===========================================================================

new_plan         — a NEW or AMENDED legislative instrument, water plan,
                   regulation, statutory rule, or subordinate instrument
                   has been made. The article states the instrument has
                   been registered, gazetted, commenced, or signed.
                   Signals: "has been made under", "commenced on",
                   "registered on", "gazetted on", "subordinate to the
                   [Act name]".

media_release    — a single media / press release from ONE agency,
                   containing at least ONE attributed quote from a
                   spokesperson, Minister, or the agency itself.
                   Signals: quoted sentences, "said [Name]",
                   "according to [Agency]", "a spokesperson advised".

weekly_report    — a PERIODIC monitoring, flow, storage, compliance,
                   or data report — weekly, monthly, or quarterly.
                   Signals: "for the week ending", "monthly compliance
                   report", "latest storage levels", "weekly flow data".

bullet_list      — MULTIPLE short releases, notices, or updates grouped
                   together under a single agency header. Typically the
                   article text itself presents them as a list.
                   Signals: "the following media releases", "recent
                   announcements include", numbered or bulleted items.

simple_update    — a single BRIEF advisory, notice, or information
                   update WITHOUT an attributed quote. Usually 1-3
                   short paragraphs reporting a factual change.
                   Signals: short length, no quote marks, purely
                   informational tone ("advises", "notes", "confirms").

gazette_bundle   — MULTIPLE gazette notices issued under ONE Act, grouped
                   in a single issue of the Government Gazette.
                   Signals: "Government Gazette No. NN", "various notices
                   have been issued", references to "pp. XX-YY" of a
                   specific gazette issue.

Content-type decision tree (walk top to bottom, first match wins):
  1. Multiple items from the Gazette under one Act       → gazette_bundle
  2. Multiple media releases under one agency header     → bullet_list
  3. Periodic (weekly/monthly/quarterly) report released → weekly_report
  4. New or amended Act / plan / regulation made         → new_plan
  5. Single release WITH a quoted spokesperson statement → media_release
  6. Single brief notice WITHOUT a quote                 → simple_update

===========================================================================
CONFIDENCE CALIBRATION
===========================================================================
Pick a confidence value that reflects the evidence in the article:

  1.00 — the article explicitly names the section topic, the jurisdiction
         (agency or Act), and the content type (e.g. "media release").
  0.85 — two of the three dimensions are explicit, one is inferred
         from strong textual evidence.
  0.70 — at least one dimension is inferred from weak signals
         (e.g. content type guessed from article length and structure).
  0.50 — major ambiguity; your answer is a reasonable guess but an
         editor should review.

IMPORTANT: Stage 6 routes any classification with confidence < 0.7 to
the editor review queue. Use confidence honestly — don't inflate it to
skip review, and don't deflate it to dodge responsibility.

